SIMPLE: equilateral
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Equilateral
<hw>E`qui*lat"er*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>aequilateralis</ets>; <ets>aequus</ets> equal + <ets>latus</ets>,
<ets>lateris</ets>, side: cf. F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧quilat⟦eacute⟧ral</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having all the sides
equal; <as>as, an <ex>equilateral</ex> triangle; an <ex>equilateral</ex>
polygon.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Equilateral hyperbola</b></col> <fld>(Geom.)</fld>,
<cd>one whose axes are equal.</cd> -- <col><b>Equilateral
shell</b></col> <fld>(Zo⟦oum⟧l.)</fld>, <cd>one in which a transverse
line drawn through the apex of the umbo bisects the valve, or divides it
into two equal and symmetrical parts.</cd> -- <col><b>Mutually
equilateral</b></col>, <cd>applied to two figures, when every side of
the one has its equal among the sides of the other.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Equilateral</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Equilateral
<hw>E`qui*lat"er*al</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A side exactly
corresponding, or equal, to others; also, a figure of equal
sides.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Equilibrate</ent>⟦br⟧
